commit.message:
Update link to specscdrom.pdf

Currently the link leads to a 404 page. Use a version archived on
web.archive.org.

Signed-off-by: Kamil Aronowski <kamil.aronowski@yahoo.com>

Manually tell it we've got 64-bit files, because 32-bit OSes need it.

Signed-off-by: Peter Jones <pjones@redhat.com>

Allow overriding various make variables

In particular, this makes it sanely possible to cross-compile dumpet.
CFLAGS etc. should normally be considered as user variables, and when
overriding compiler flags the user shouldn't have to add pkg-config
output manually to make things work.

Signed-off-by: Colin Watson <cjwatson@canonical.com>
Add partition flag printing code to applepart.

Add all the flags we see in the wild to libapplepart.h

Not that I'm entirely sure about either MAC_PARTITION_OS_SPECIFIC_0 or
MAC_PARTITION_DUMMY, but we see them, we may as well preliminarily name
them.

Flesh out name/type getters and setters.

Also use them in the test program.

"make clean" should clean apmtest.

Because otherwise pasting the output at people looks weird.

Quit making public getters by hand.

This is one of the few tasks cpp is good at.  Use it.
Also in this commit:
- Stubs for private getter/setter for partition name and type
- A bit more debugging info.

Flesh out some more test cases for apple partitions.

In particular, make the read test tell us something about partitions,
and explicitly split it out as a read test so we can have other tests
later.

Fix compile errors in _adl_add_partition()

Obviously, I never ran make yesterday.

Add adl_add_partition()

Add a routine to add a partition.

Add flags get/set functions.

Add getters and setters for the partition flags, and move their
definitions to the public header.

Make it so you can use "make TOOL=cachegrind" or whatnot.

In case memcheck isn't what we're looking for...

Set each newly-read partition entry's Label pointer to the AppleDiskLabel.

Set Partition[n]->Label = adl, and also be more thorough about clearing
the parititon's memory in a failure case.

Add a small test suite for apple partition maps.

This may have to change later, since obviously I haven't (and can't
legally) commited the test data.

Add partition map reading and some verification.

Flesh out adl_read() and make it read and verify signatures and
partition signatures.

Get rid of libapplepart_p.h , it wasn't worth it.

The file literally wasn't worth the screen real estate it took to
maintain it; merge it in with applepart.h which is private anyway.

Add the very beginnings of support for apple blessed CD type media.

It's not complete yet, but it's a bare-bones start.
Add beginnings of headers for apple partitioning support.

Bump version to 2.1

A new release means a new version bump.

Add NeXT/Apple support to the TODO.

Since I should be using this to keep track...

Document -h and -x options in --help output

-h only has any useful effect if -x isn't given, so list these as
alternatives.

Signed-off-by: Colin Watson <cjwatson@canonical.com>

Add manual page

Slight typo, sorry - please use the following instead.

Signed-off-by: Colin Watson <cjwatson@canonical.com>

Use 'install -D'

This makes packaging fractionally less effort, and seems like good style.

Signed-off-by: Colin Watson <cjwatson@canonical.com>

Add an "upload" target.

I can't ever remember how to do a "release", so add a makefile target
for it.

Bump version to 2.0

This is the 2.0 release.  It is awesome and adds XML output in order to
support automated validation of CD images.

Add "-x" support for dumping XML blobs.

"-x" or "--xml" now dumps the El Torito boot catalog as XML.
If you use "-d", it'll also include the actual boot images in the XML
blob.

Make the Makefile do pkg-config stuff for libxml2.

First step in xml support - include directories and linking.

Improve load segment display on x86.

log from irc (with some editing):
<pjones> I religiously copied what the spec says (which is 0x7c0), but
         the actual value in the table is 0
<hpa> Yeah, it's a buglet in the spec
<hpa> Real BIOSes -- with a few exceptions -- use 0000:7C00 when the
      value is 0, but 07C0:0000 when the value is 0x7c0
<pjones> (0 just happens to be a code for the address when platformid=0)
<pjones> do they also care about other magic values, or is it actually
         "0000:7c00 if the value is 0, $VAL:0000 for anything else"?
<hpa> It's the latter

With that in mind, it's now displaying the raw value and the
interpreted value.
Fix return checking on asprintf
